"""
mkt-original layer: Joshua 21–23.
95 verses: ch 21 (45), ch 22 (34), ch 23 (16).
Key terms: migrash (pasturelands), miqlat (city of refuge), menuha (rest),
ma'al (breach of faith), ed/edut (witness/testimony), dabaq (cling),
lo nafal davar (not one word failed).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ORIGINAL = {
  "21": {
    "1": "<p><strong>vayigshu rashei avot haLviim el Eleazar hakohen</strong>: &lsquo;the heads of the Levitical fathers came to Eleazar the priest&rsquo; — the petition is presented to the right authority (Eleazar the priest, not Joshua alone), consistent with Numbers 35&rsquo;s assignment of the Levitical cities as a priestly matter. The Levites&rsquo; request initiates the last major land-distribution act. Unlike the tribal allotments, the Levitical cities are not a homeland but a dispersal: forty-eight cities spread through all twelve tribes, so that the priestly service function is distributed across the entire nation. The design prevents the concentration of priestly power in one location while ensuring that every tribe has access to Levitical instruction.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>tzavah YHWH beyad Moshe latet lanu arim lashevet umigrasheichen</strong>: &lsquo;YHWH commanded through Moses to give us cities to live in, with pasturelands for our livestock&rsquo; — the petition is grounded in prior divine command (Num 35:1-8), not in general need. The Levites are not asking for generosity but invoking an obligation: YHWH promised this through Moses. The <em>migrash</em> (pastureland, grazing area) attached to each city is a technical land term — a strip of common land surrounding the city, not for agriculture but for livestock. The Levites&rsquo; material provision is specified to prevent their dependence on tribal agriculture while preserving their availability for priestly service.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>vayitnu bnei Yisrael laLviim min nachalatam al pi YHWH</strong>: &lsquo;the Israelites gave the Levites from their inheritance at YHWH&rsquo;s command&rsquo; — the giving is from tribal allotments: each tribe contributes cities to the Levites from land already apportioned to them. This is the mechanism of Numbers 35:8 (in proportion to the inheritance each tribe receives, so the cities it gives). The obedience formula <em>al pi YHWH</em> (at the mouth of YHWH) marks the transaction as covenant compliance, not tribal generosity. Israel is not doing the Levites a favor but honoring a divine arrangement.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>vayetze hagoral lemishpachot haQehati</strong>: &lsquo;the lot fell for the Kohathite families&rsquo; — the three Levitical clans (Kohath, Gershon, Merari) receive their cities by lot, introducing the element of divine determination into the geographic distribution. The Kohathites (Moses and Aaron&rsquo;s clan) receive first; within the Kohathites, the Aaronite priestly line receives thirteen cities from Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin — the southern tribes closest to Jerusalem, anticipating the future centralization of priestly service at the Davidic temple. The distribution is not random but providentially positioned.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The remaining Kohathite families (non-priestly Kohathites who carried the ark and furnishings in the wilderness) received ten cities from Ephraim, Dan, and half-Manasseh. The geographic distribution of non-priestly Kohathites in the central and northern territories corresponds to the areas with the highest subsequent need for Levitical teaching. The later turbulence of the northern kingdom (1 Kings 12:31 — Jeroboam&rsquo;s non-Levitical priests) will confirm that the loss of Levitical presence had devastating consequences.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Gershonites received thirteen cities from Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, and the half-tribe of Manasseh in Bashan — the northern and Transjordan territories. The Gershonites had carried the tabernacle&rsquo;s coverings and curtains in the wilderness; their placement in the north distributes the priestly tradition through the tribal areas most geographically distant from the future temple. The provision for Levites in remote areas is an infrastructure decision: the covenant is not a Jerusalem-only institution.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Merarites received twelve cities from Reuben, Gad, and Zebulun — spanning both sides of the Jordan. The Merarites carried the tabernacle&rsquo;s structural components (boards, bars, pillars) in the wilderness; their placement in the Transjordan tribes and the northern plain ensures that the tribal territories that would otherwise have the weakest Levitical connection are served. The geographic intentionality of the distribution becomes apparent when mapped: no tribal territory is without Levitical cities.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>vayitnu bnei Yisrael et he'arim ha'eleh vegidrotheichen laLviim kal asher tzivah YHWH beyad Moshe</strong>: &lsquo;the Israelites gave these cities and their pasturelands to the Levites, just as YHWH commanded through Moses&rsquo; — summary formula closing the introduction before the detailed city lists. The double attribution — to Israel&rsquo;s act and to YHWH&rsquo;s prior command — is characteristic of Joshua&rsquo;s narrative theology: human obedience and divine institution are simultaneous, not competing.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The city list begins with Judah and Simeon — the tribes whose territory overlaps and who together provide the first set of Aaronite cities. The narrative precision of the city lists (naming each city individually rather than describing regions) creates a verifiable record: the Levitical distribution is not a literary ideal but a documented historical reality. The specificity also serves a mnemonic function: these cities with their Levitical connections were part of Israel&rsquo;s institutional memory.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The descendants of Aaron receive the first lot — the priestly line within the Kohathites. The narrative re-identifies them as Kohathite Levites to clarify the clan structure: all Aaronites are Kohathites, but not all Kohathites are Aaronites. The structural precision matters because the distinction between priestly Kohathites (Aaron&rsquo;s line) and non-priestly Kohathites (other Kohathite families) is the fundamental division of Levitical function: proximity to the altar is reserved for Aaron&rsquo;s sons.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>et Qiryat Arba avi haAnak hi Chevron</strong>: &lsquo;Kiriath-arba, which is Hebron — Arba was the forefather of Anak&rsquo; — Hebron&rsquo;s double identification (both names, with genealogical note) is consistent with Joshua&rsquo;s practice of noting the pre-Israelite names of significant sites. Hebron is significant because it was Caleb&rsquo;s personal allotment (14:13-14) and David&rsquo;s first capital (2 Sam 2:1-4). The Levitical city and Caleb&rsquo;s personal holding coexist: the city itself (with its pasturelands) goes to the Levites; the fields and villages of the surrounding territory go to Caleb (v12).</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>vesedeh hair vegidroteiha natan Calev ben Yefuneh biachuzato</strong>: &lsquo;but the fields and villages they gave to Caleb son of Jephunneh as his personal possession&rsquo; — the distinction between the city proper (including its immediate pasturelands) and the surrounding agricultural territory is precise. Caleb retains his promised inheritance; the Levites receive the city as a residence and service base. The two claims do not conflict because they operate at different scales: the city for Levitical habitation, the territory for Calebite agriculture. The careful demarcation reflects the actual administrative complexity of land tenure in ancient Israel.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>uvnei Aharon hakohen natan et Chevron ir miqlashot haroteach</strong>: &lsquo;to the descendants of Aaron the priest they gave Hebron — a city of refuge for the manslayer&rsquo; — the overlap of Levitical city and city of refuge is deliberate: in the priestly territories, the places of asylum are also places of priestly presence. The manslayer who flees to a city of refuge is in a space where priestly mediation is immediately available — not merely protected from the blood-avenger, but in the presence of those who can adjudicate the case and provide atonement.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jattir and Eshtemoa with their pasturelands — cities in the southern hill country of Judah. The names of these cities become part of the record of David&rsquo;s distribution of plunder to the elders of Judah after Ziklag (1 Sam 30:27-28): Eshtemoa appears in that list, connecting the later Davidic history to the Levitical city network. The Levitical cities were centers of community life, not isolated priestly enclaves.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Holon and Debir — cities in the Judahite hill country. Debir (Kiriath-sepher) was taken by Othniel, Caleb&rsquo;s nephew, as the first judge-act of the conquest period (Josh 15:15-19). Its assignment here as a Levitical city means that the site of the first conquest-by-faith becomes a center of priestly presence and instruction. The geography of redemptive history accumulates meaning: places where YHWH acted become places where YHWH is taught.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Ain, Juttah, Beth-shemesh — completing the nine cities from Judah and Simeon for the Aaronite priests. Beth-shemesh (House of the Sun) will later be the destination of the ark when it is returned by the Philistines (1 Sam 6:12-19). The event at Beth-shemesh — where men were struck dead for looking into the ark — demonstrates that the Levitical city designation did not guarantee correct priestly practice; the presence of a Levitical city is the institutional provision, but faithfulness to its covenant function is always contingent.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Gibeon and Geba from Benjamin — significant sites. Gibeon was the city of the Hivite deception (ch 9) and will become the location of the tabernacle during David&rsquo;s reign (1 Chr 16:39; 21:29). Geba is a strategic pass in Benjamin&rsquo;s territory that will appear in later military narratives. The Levitical cities are often at geographic and strategic crossroads — not coincidentally, since the need for priestly presence and legal adjudication would be highest at places of significant movement and exchange.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Anathoth and Almon from Benjamin — Anathoth is the priestly city where Jeremiah was born (Jer 1:1). The prophet&rsquo;s identification as &ldquo;the son of Hilkiah, of the priests who were in Anathoth&rdquo; (Jer 1:1) places his origin within the Levitical city network. Jeremiah&rsquo;s conflict with the temple establishment and his radical critique of Judah&rsquo;s covenant failures emerges from within the priestly tradition, not outside it — a priest&rsquo;s son speaking covenant truth that the temple priests refused to hear.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>kol arei bnei Aharon hakohanim shlosha esre ir umigrasheichen</strong>: &lsquo;all the cities of the priestly line of Aaron: thirteen with their pasturelands&rsquo; — the summary closes the Aaronite section. Thirteen cities for the priests; the number is not round (unlike the Kohathite non-priestly ten, the Gershonite thirteen, and the Merarite twelve) because priestly cities follow tribal availability. The careful accounting — tribe by tribe, subtotal by subtotal — reflects a genuine administrative record of the Levitical distribution.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The non-priestly Kohathites begin their section. &ldquo;The rest of the Kohathite Levites&rdquo; distinguishes them from Aaron&rsquo;s descendants: these are the families who carried the ark and the furniture of the inner sanctuary (Num 4:4-15). Their placement in Ephraim, Dan, and half-Manasseh positions the carriers of the ark in the central hill country, which will later be the territory of the divided monarchy&rsquo;s northern kingdom — a providential distribution for the period when the ark&rsquo;s significance will be most contested.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>et Shekem ir miqlat laroteach behar Efrayim</strong>: &lsquo;they gave them Shechem — a city of refuge — in the hill country of Ephraim&rsquo; — Shechem as a non-priestly Kohathite city and city of refuge places the second city of asylum in Ephraim, the dominant northern tribe. Shechem&rsquo;s long history (Gen 12:6, 33:18, ch 34, the Dinah incident; Josh 24, the covenant renewal) makes it a natural center for the Levitical presence in the north. The assembly of Israel in ch 24 will gather here, and the Levitical presence is the institutional framework within which that assembly is possible.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Kibzaim and Beth-horon from Ephraim — four cities total for the non-priestly Kohathites in Ephraim. Beth-horon (both Upper and Lower) is a strategic pass connecting the central hills to the coastal plain and the site of significant military actions (Josh 10:10-11; 1 Sam 13:18; 1 Macc 3:16). Levitical cities at strategic passes serve as waypoints of priestly presence along major travel routes.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Eltekeh and Gibbethon from Dan — cities in the Shephelah (lowland) region between the hill country and the coast. Dan&rsquo;s territory was notoriously difficult to hold (15:63; Judg 1:34) and eventually caused the Danite migration northward (Judg 18). The Levitical cities in Dan were in a contested zone, and the tribe&rsquo;s failure to control its territory meant the Levitical infrastructure there was compromised from early on.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Aijalon and Gath-rimmon from Dan — completing the four Danite cities for the non-priestly Kohathites. Aijalon is the valley where the sun stood still (Josh 10:12). The connection between miraculous divine intervention and Levitical city is characteristic of Joshua&rsquo;s narrative: the sites of great acts become places where the covenant is taught and the acts are remembered.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Taanach and Gath-rimmon from half-Manasseh — two cities. The name Gath-rimmon appears twice in vv24-25 (from Dan and from half-Manasseh) and 1 Chronicles 6:69 changes the Manassite city to Ibleam, suggesting a scribal error in one of the two occurrences. The textual variant is one of the few points where the Levitical city lists show divergence between Joshua and 1 Chronicles 6, providing evidence for copyist variation in lists of geographic names.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>kol arim asarah umigrasheichen limishpachot bnei Qehat hanotirim</strong>: &lsquo;all the cities of the remaining Kohathite families: ten with their pasturelands&rsquo; — the subtotal closes the non-priestly Kohathite section. Ten cities for the carrying-families of the inner sanctuary, plus thirteen for the Aaronite priests, equals twenty-three Kohathite cities total — almost half the forty-eight. The disproportionate Kohathite share reflects their double function: priestly service (Aaron&rsquo;s line) and ark-bearing (the rest of Kohath).</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>ulivnei Gershon mimishpachot haLevi minchatzi shevet haMenashe et Golan baBashan ir miqlat</strong>: &lsquo;to the Gershonite Levites, from the other half-tribe of Manasseh: Golan in Bashan — a city of refuge&rsquo; — Golan in Bashan is the third city of refuge (of six), placed in the Transjordan. The Gershonites receive the northern and Transjordan territory, distributing the priestly tradition to the areas furthest from the future Jerusalem temple. Golan&rsquo;s modern prominence (the Golan Heights) reflects its strategic importance, which ancient Israel&rsquo;s land distribution recognized by placing a Levitical city there.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Kishon and Daberath from Issachar — cities in the Jezreel Valley. The Jezreel Valley is one of the most fertile and strategically significant regions of ancient Canaan, the site of the battle of Megiddo (Judg 5) and numerous subsequent military engagements. Levitical cities in the Jezreel Valley place priestly presence at the agricultural and military heart of the northern territory.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Jarmuth and En-gannim from Issachar — completing the four Issachar cities for the Gershonites. En-gannim (&ldquo;spring of gardens&rdquo;) near the Jezreel Valley&rsquo;s access point continues the pattern of Levitical cities at geographically significant locations. The spring (<em>ein</em>) names in the Levitical city list reflect the practical requirement that communities of any size need reliable water sources — a mundane material consideration woven into the sacred institutional structure.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Mishal and Abdon from Asher — cities in the coastal foothills of the northern coastal territory. Asher&rsquo;s territory along the Phoenician coast was notoriously difficult to secure from indigenous populations (Judg 1:31-32), and the Levitical cities in Asher were in a mixed zone where the covenant instruction would be most needed and most challenged.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Helkath and Rehob from Asher — completing the four Asher cities. The Gershonite cities in Asher and Naphtali position the priestly carrying-families in the northernmost tribal territories, the region that will first fall to Assyrian conquest (2 Kings 15:29). The Levitical network in the north is both the institutional provision for those territories and a measure of what was lost when Assyria depopulated them.</p>",
    "32": "<p><strong>veQedesh baGalil ir miqlat laroteach</strong>: &lsquo;Kedesh in Galilee — a city of refuge&rsquo; — Kedesh of Galilee is the fourth city of refuge, in the northern territory that Jesus will inhabit (&ldquo;Galilee of the Gentiles&rdquo;, Matt 4:15). The city of refuge in Galilee makes the northern territory, with its highest concentration of non-Israelite population, a place where the asylum principle applies. The geographic reach of the <em>miqlat</em> cities — from Hebron in the south to Kedesh in the far north, and from Bezer in the Transjordan to Shechem in the central hill country — reflects the intent that the asylum provision cover all of the land.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>kol arei haGershuni lemishpachtam shlosha asher ir umigrasheichen</strong>: &lsquo;all the cities of the Gershonites by their families: thirteen with their pasturelands&rsquo; — the Gershonite subtotal matches the Aaronite total (thirteen each), though covering a different geographic range. The northern distribution of the Gershonites creates a priestly presence network across the territories that will later constitute the northern kingdom of Israel — where the eight Levitical cities of the Gershonites should have been centers of covenant instruction preventing the Jeroboam apostasy.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The Merarites receive cities from Zebulun — beginning the last Levitical clan&rsquo;s distribution. The Merarites carried the structural components of the tabernacle (boards, bars, pillars, bases) in the wilderness — the heaviest loads, the load-bearing elements. Their cities in Zebulun and Reuben and Gad cover the tribal territories flanking the Jezreel Valley on the north and the Transjordan. Jokneam is at the southwestern entrance to the Jezreel Valley; Kartah is uncertain in location. The structural-carrier families settle in the structural hinge-points of the land&rsquo;s geography.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Dimnah and Nahalal from Zebulun — completing the four Zebulun cities for the Merarites. Nahalal is the site from which Zebulun could not drive out the Canaanites (Judg 1:30); a Levitical city in a zone of incomplete conquest is a measure of the ongoing challenge of covenant faithfulness in mixed zones. The Levitical infrastructure existed; the tribal will to maintain separation was inconsistent.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Bezer and Jahaz from Reuben — Bezer being the fifth city of refuge, in the Transjordan. Bezer (<em>bezer</em> = ore/strong place) in the wilderness of the plateau was the city of asylum for the Transjordan region. Jahaz was the site of Israel&rsquo;s victory over Sihon king of the Amorites (Num 21:23) — the battle that opened the Transjordan conquest. The location of a Levitical city at a site of decisive divine victory is consistent with the pattern of placing priestly instruction at sites where YHWH acted decisively.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Kedemoth and Mephaath from Reuben — completing the four Reubenite cities. Kedemoth is associated with Moses&rsquo;s wilderness preaching (Deut 2:26) and the failed negotiation with Sihon. The accumulation of historic associations in the Levitical city names is significant: these are not arbitrary geographic assignments but sites whose histories are intertwined with Israel&rsquo;s foundational narrative. The Levitical presence in these cities connects the priestly instruction to the remembered acts of YHWH.</p>",
    "38": "<p><strong>umimat Gad Ramot baGilad ir miqlat laroteach</strong>: &lsquo;from Gad: Ramoth in Gilead — a city of refuge&rsquo; — Ramoth Gilead is the sixth and last city of refuge, in the Gadite territory of the Transjordan. Ramoth Gilead will later be the site of repeated Israelite-Aramean conflict (1 Kings 22:1-38; 2 Kings 8:28-29; 9:1-15), the city Ahab dies trying to reclaim and where Elijah anoints Jehu. The city of refuge that was to protect the innocent becomes the site of Ahab&rsquo;s unjust death — irony within the book&rsquo;s later history.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Heshbon and Jazer from Gad — Heshbon being the former capital of Sihon king of the Amorites, whose conquest opened the Transjordan (Num 21:25-26). The assignment of Sihon&rsquo;s capital to the Merarites as a Levitical city is a transformative act: the seat of pagan kingship becomes a center of Levitical instruction. The same transformation principle governs the broader conquest narrative: places of pagan power are consecrated to YHWH&rsquo;s service.</p>",
    "40": "<p><strong>kol ha'arim livnei Merari lemishpachtam hanotirim mimmishpachot haLevi vayehi goralham arim shtem esreh</strong>: &lsquo;all the cities assigned to the Merarites by their families — the remaining Levitical families — were twelve&rsquo; — the Merarite subtotal closes the clan-by-clan distribution. Twelve cities for the structural-carriers, completing the tallying that has proceeded with administrative precision through the chapter. The four subtotals (13 + 10 + 13 + 12 = 48) account for all the Levitical cities.</p>",
    "41": "<p><strong>kol arei haLviim bithoch achuzat bnei Yisrael arbaim ushmone ir umigrasheichen</strong>: &lsquo;the total number of Levitical cities within Israelite territory: forty-eight cities with their pasturelands&rsquo; — the grand total. Forty-eight is four times twelve: four clans (Aaron, non-priestly Kohath, Gershon, Merari) times twelve tribes (or a variant allocation), though the actual distribution is not uniform across tribes. The number&rsquo;s divisibility by twelve creates a symmetry: the covenant community structured by twelve receives a priestly service network with the same numerical resonance. Numbers as structural markers carry theological weight in the priestly organization of Israel.</p>",
    "42": "<p><strong>he'arim ha'eleh ir ir umigrasheichen saviv lahem ken lehol he'arim ha'eleh</strong>: &lsquo;every one of these cities had its surrounding pasturelands — it was the same for all these cities&rsquo; — the uniformity clause closes the administrative section. The <em>migrash</em> (pastureland) attached to every Levitical city ensures that each one is functionally complete: the Levites can maintain their livestock and sustain their communities without dependence on individual tribal hospitality. The structural provision for the priestly tribe is comprehensive and equitable.</p>",
    "43": "<p><strong>vayiten YHWH leYisrael et kol ha'aretz asher nishba latet la'avotam</strong>: &lsquo;the LORD gave Israel all the land that he had sworn to give their ancestors&rsquo; — the first of three fulfillment declarations that close chapters 21-23. The land-promise to Abraham (Gen 12:7; 15:18-21; 17:8), Isaac (Gen 26:3), and Jacob (Gen 28:13) is now fulfilled in the tribal allotments and Levitical cities just described. The word <em>nishba</em> (swore by oath) frames the fulfillment in terms of divine fidelity: this is not contingent provision but oath-keeping.</p>",
    "44": "<p><strong>vayanuach YHWH lahem misaviv kekhol asher nishba la'avotam</strong>: &lsquo;the LORD gave them rest on every side, just as he had sworn to their ancestors&rsquo; — the second fulfillment declaration introduces <em>menuha</em> (rest, the same word as Deut 12:9 and the Sabbath-rest motif that runs through the OT). The promise was not just land but rest in the land — cessation of the warfare and displacement that characterized the wilderness generation. The rest here is partial and provisional (the incompletely conquered Canaanites remain); Hebrews 4:8 argues that the incompleteness of Joshua&rsquo;s rest proves a greater rest remains.</p>",
    "45": "<p><strong>lo nafal davar mikol hadavar hatov asher diber YHWH el beit Yisrael hakol ba</strong>: &lsquo;not one word of all the good things that YHWH spoke concerning the house of Israel failed; all came to pass&rsquo; — the third and most comprehensive fulfillment declaration. <em>Lo nafal davar</em> (not one word fell) uses the verb <em>nafal</em> (fall) metaphorically: words are things that stand or fall; YHWH&rsquo;s words stand forever (Isa 40:8: &ldquo;the word of our God will stand forever&rdquo;). Joshua 21:45 is the OT&rsquo;s most comprehensive testimony to divine promise-faithfulness, and 2 Cor 1:20 (&ldquo;all the promises of God find their Yes in him&rdquo;) is its NT equivalent and ultimate basis.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>Joshua summons the Reubenites, Gadites, and half-tribe of Manasseh — the Transjordan tribes who had agreed to help with the conquest before receiving their territory east of the Jordan (Num 32; Josh 1:12-18). The formal summoning signals a formal occasion: this is the dismissal ceremony, the completion of the obligation. The narrative takes the word-keeping of these tribes as the model of covenant fidelity to be honored and commended before the whole assembly.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>atem shemartem et kol asher tzivah Moshe eved YHWH etchem</strong>: &lsquo;you have kept all that Moses the servant of YHWH commanded you&rsquo; — Joshua&rsquo;s opening commendation is total: <em>et kol</em>, all that was commanded. This is the highest possible evaluation — complete covenant fidelity. The Transjordan tribes, who might have been tempted to return to their own territory once it was secured, chose instead to fulfill their commitment through the years of the western conquest. Their loyalty is now formally recognized before the whole congregation.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>lo azavtem et acheichem zeh yamim rabim ad hayom hazeh</strong>: &lsquo;you have not deserted your brothers these many days, right up to this day&rsquo; — the time qualification (&ldquo;these many days&rdquo;) acknowledges the sacrifice involved: years away from home, wives, children, and livestock in their own territory, while serving in the western campaign. Faithfulness that endures over time, not just in the initial enthusiasm of commitment, is the quality Joshua commends. The same quality governs the NT call to perseverance: &ldquo;let us not grow weary of doing good&rdquo; (Gal 6:9).</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>veattah heniyach YHWH Eloheichem le'acheichem ka'asher diber lahem</strong>: &lsquo;now the LORD your God has given rest to your brothers as he promised them&rsquo; — the dismissal is grounded in divine fulfillment: the rest has been given. The Transjordan tribes can go home not because they chose to leave early but because the purpose of their service is complete. Joshua&rsquo;s release of them is simultaneous with YHWH&rsquo;s fulfillment of the rest-promise. Timing the release to the fulfillment of the purpose is itself an act of covenant honor.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>rak shimru me'od la'asot et hamitzvah ve'et hatorah asher tzivah Moshe eved YHWH le'ahavah et YHWH Eloheichem ulelechet bekol derachav velishmor mitzvotav udovqah vo ule'ovdo bechol levavchem uvechol nafshchem</strong>: &lsquo;only be very careful to observe the commandment and the law… to love YHWH your God, walk in all his ways, keep his commandments, cling to him, and serve him with all your heart and soul&rsquo; — the parting charge is the fullest statement of covenant obligation in Joshua, a near-verbatim anticipation of the Shema&rsquo;s full form. The five verbs (love, walk, keep, cling, serve) cover the full range of covenantal response. <em>Dabaq</em> (cling) is the same verb used in Gen 2:24 (&ldquo;a man shall leave his father and mother and cling to his wife&rdquo;) — covenant faithfulness is as intimate as marriage.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>vayevarechem Yehoshua vayishlachem vayelechu el ohaleihem</strong>: &lsquo;Joshua blessed them and sent them on their way, and they went to their tents&rsquo; — the blessing and dismissal completes the formal ceremony. The Transjordan tribes depart with Joshua&rsquo;s blessing — the same blessing that Moses gave in Deut 33 before his death. The narrative places Joshua in the Moses-role: the one who blesses the departing people at the completion of the redemptive act.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The narrative notes a particular complexity: Moses had given the eastern half of Manasseh land in Bashan, but Joshua had given the western half of Manasseh land in Canaan proper. The same tribe straddles both sides of the Jordan — a geographic expression of the mixed situation of the Transjordan arrangement. The blessing was for both halves, the charge was the same, but the territories are separated by the river that Israel crossed as a covenant act.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>shuvú el ohaleihem becharmishah rabah</strong>: &lsquo;return to your homes with great wealth&rsquo; — the dismissal includes material provision: livestock, silver, gold, bronze, iron, clothing — the plunder of the western campaign divided with the Transjordanites. The instruction to divide the plunder with your brothers is a cross-reference to the principle of Num 31:27 (split the plunder between the soldiers who went to battle and the rest of the congregation). Those who serve on the front lines share their gain with the community; those who remain share with those who went.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Transjordan tribes depart from Shiloh — the tabernacle&rsquo;s location in the west — and cross back into Gilead, their own territory. The phrase &ldquo;the land of their possession, which they received according to the commandment of YHWH through Moses&rdquo; emphasizes the legitimacy of their eastern territory: it was YHWH&rsquo;s assignment through Moses, not a second-best compromise. The narrative is careful to not treat the Transjordan settlement as a failure or an inferior arrangement.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>vayavou el gelilot haYarden asher be'eretz Kena'an vayivnu bnei Reuven uvnei Gad vachazi shevet haMenashe sham mizbeach al haYarden</strong>: &lsquo;they came to the region of the Jordan in the land of Canaan and built an altar there by the Jordan&rsquo; — the altar is built on the Canaanite side of the Jordan (&ldquo;the land of Canaan&rdquo;) before crossing over — deliberately visible to the western tribes. The location matters: it is not hidden in Gilead but positioned as a visible marker at the border. The intent (as revealed in v24-28) is to be seen by both sides.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The report reaches the Israelites: the Transjordan tribes have built an altar &ldquo;at the frontier of the land of Canaan in the region about the Jordan, on the side belonging to the people of Israel&rdquo; — the geography of the altar&rsquo;s location is already potentially inflammatory. An altar on the Canaanite side of the Jordan could mean an attempt to establish a rival sacrificial site, directly violating the centralization principle of Deut 12 (you shall not offer your burnt offerings in every place that you see).</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>vayishme'u bnei Yisrael vayiqahel kol adat bnei Yisrael Shiloh la'alot aleihem latzava</strong>: &lsquo;the entire assembly of the Israelites gathered at Shiloh to go up against them in war&rsquo; — the immediate response of the western tribes is military: the altar constitutes a potential covenant breach serious enough to justify civil war. The assembly at Shiloh — the location of the tabernacle — grounds the military threat in covenantal authority: the community gathers at the place of YHWH&rsquo;s presence to prosecute YHWH&rsquo;s cause. The speed of the response demonstrates how seriously the covenant centralization of worship was taken.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Before going to war, the Israelites send a delegation — Phinehas and ten leaders. The substitution of diplomacy for immediate war is itself a covenantal act: the law required attempted reconciliation before conflict. Phinehas is the ideal delegate: he is the priest who demonstrated covenantal zeal at Peor (Num 25:7-8) and whose covenant of peace (Num 25:12-13) made him YHWH&rsquo;s faithful instrument against covenant violation. He represents both the prosecution of covenant faithfulness and the possibility of restoration.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The ten leaders — one from each tribe of Israel — represent the covenantal whole in the delegation. The number ten for the tribal representation alongside Phinehas reflects the structure of Numbers 13-14, where tribal representatives went ahead. The delegation is an act of solidarity: the covenant community acts together, through its representative leaders, rather than through mob action or unilateral military decision.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The delegation arrives in Gilead and addresses the Reubenites, Gadites, and half-Manasseh. The dramatic confrontation is between Israelites — not between Israel and Canaanites. The danger of the situation is precisely that the covenant community is fracturing from within. The altar at the Jordan, whatever its intent, has created a crisis of communal solidarity that is more threatening than external enemies.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>mah hama'al hazeh asher me'altem be'Elohei Yisrael</strong>: &lsquo;what is this breach of faith (<em>ma'al</em>) that you have committed against the God of Israel?&rsquo; — <em>ma'al</em> is the same term used of Achan&rsquo;s theft (7:1) and of unauthorized use of sacred things in Leviticus 5. The accusation is specific and serious: this is not mere civil conflict but a trespass against the sacred. The delegation presents the strongest possible interpretation of the altar&rsquo;s significance — a charitable impulse requires giving the accused the chance to explain, not presuming guilt — while naming what would be true if the worst interpretation were correct.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>hameut lanu et avon Peor</strong>: &lsquo;is the sin of Peor too small for us?&rsquo; — the reference to the Baal Peor apostasy (Num 25) invokes the most recent devastating covenant failure, which killed 24,000 people and which Phinehas himself had stopped with his spear. The delegation&rsquo;s appeal to Peor&rsquo;s memory is simultaneously a warning (that&rsquo;s what covenant violation produces) and a confession: &ldquo;we have not fully cleansed ourselves of it.&rdquo; The community&rsquo;s moral accountability for past covenant failures is presented as an ongoing weight.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>veattim tashuvu hayom me'acharei YHWH vehayah atem tomredu hayom baYHWH umachar el kol adat Yisrael yiqtzof</strong>: &lsquo;and if you rebel against the LORD today, tomorrow he will be angry at the whole assembly of Israel&rsquo; — the delegation articulates the principle of corporate solidarity in covenant: one tribe&rsquo;s sin affects the whole assembly. This is not arbitrary collective punishment but the nature of covenant membership: the community is one body, and infection in one part spreads to the whole (cf. 1 Cor 5:6: &ldquo;a little leaven leavens the whole lump&rdquo;). The concern for the whole assembly&rsquo;s welfare drives the confrontation.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>ve'im teme'ah artzechem ivru lachem el eretz achuzat YHWH asher shaken bo mishkan YHWH</strong>: &lsquo;if your land is unclean, come over into the land of the LORD&rsquo;s possession where the LORD&rsquo;s tabernacle dwells&rsquo; — the remarkable offer: if the Transjordan territory cannot support proper worship, the western tribes will make room for you among us. The offer reveals that the delegation&rsquo;s primary concern is covenant fidelity, not territorial defensiveness. The principle that access to YHWH&rsquo;s tabernacle matters more than tribal territory is a covenant priority that the NT confirms: &ldquo;do not give up meeting together&rdquo; (Heb 10:25) — proximity to the assembly of God&rsquo;s people is worth significant sacrifice.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>halo Achan ben Zerah ma'al ma'al bachareim veal kol adat Yisrael hayah qatzef</strong>: &lsquo;did not Achan son of Zerah commit a trespass regarding the devoted things, and wrath came upon the whole congregation of Israel?&rsquo; — the Achan precedent is invoked precisely: one man&rsquo;s <em>ma'al</em> brought YHWH&rsquo;s anger upon the whole assembly, and &ldquo;he was not the only one who died for his iniquity.&rdquo; The delegation is not threatening the Transjordan tribes but warning them about the corporate consequences of what YHWH&rsquo;s judgment looks like when covenant breach goes unaddressed.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>vaya'anu bnei Reuven uvnei Gad vachazi shebet haMenashe</strong>: the Transjordan tribes answer the delegation — their response will be decisive for the outcome. The three-tribe unity in the response mirrors the three-tribe unity of the altar&rsquo;s construction; they act as one in explanation as they did in building. The answer begins with the solemn divine invocation of v22 before the explanation of v24.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>el Elohim YHWH el Elohim YHWH hu yodea veYisrael hu yeda</strong>: &lsquo;The Mighty One, God, the LORD! The Mighty One, God, the LORD! He knows, and let Israel know!&rsquo; — the triple divine name invocation (<em>el, elohim, YHWH</em>) is the most solemn oath formula in the text. The repetition of the triple name twice creates a six-element invocation of divine witness. The declaration &ldquo;he knows&rdquo; (<em>hu yodea</em>) appeals to divine omniscience as the ultimate court of appeal: if they have sinned, God knows; if they have not sinned, God knows. The accusation that requires YHWH as witness is the highest possible formal denial.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The denial is categorical: if the altar was for burnt offerings or grain offerings or sacrifices — if it was an attempt to establish an independent sacrificial site — then &ldquo;may the LORD himself call us to account.&rdquo; The conditional self-imprecation (calling YHWH&rsquo;s judgment on themselves if they are guilty) is the formal structure of oath-taking in ancient Near Eastern legal contexts. By swearing this oath, they place themselves under divine judgment for lying — the highest possible guarantee of truthfulness.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>ume'da'agah midavar patzinu et zot</strong>: &lsquo;but we did this out of anxiety (<em>midavar da'agah</em>), for a specific reason&rsquo; — the anxiety is about future exclusion: &ldquo;your children may in time say to our children, &lsquo;What have you to do with the LORD, the God of Israel?&rsquo;&rdquo; The concern is intergenerational covenant exclusion — the fear that the Jordan river will become a theological boundary as well as a geographic one. The future-generation concern reveals covenantal thinking: they are building for their descendants&rsquo; covenant security, not for their own present advantage.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>gevul sam YHWH beinenu uveneichem bnei Reuven uvnei Gad et haYarden ein lachem cheleq baYHWH</strong>: &lsquo;the LORD has made the Jordan a border between us and you — you have no portion in the LORD&rsquo; — this is the feared future exclusion, put in the mouths of the western tribes&rsquo; children. The Jordan as theological boundary rather than merely geographic boundary would mean that the Transjordan tribes&rsquo; covenant status depends on their geographic location rather than their YHWH-allegiance. The altar is a physical counter-argument to this feared interpretation.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>vayomru nivneh lanu et mizbeach lo le'olah velo lezevach</strong>: &lsquo;we said, let us build an altar — but not for burnt offerings or sacrifices&rsquo; — the explicit denial that the altar is for sacrifice distinguishes it from a rival sanctuary. The altar as witness rather than altar as worship-site is a category that Deuteronomy 12 does not address: the centralization law prohibits sacrificial worship outside the chosen place, not commemorative or testimonial monuments. The Transjordan tribes are drawing a legal distinction between a sacrificial altar and a witness-altar.</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>ki ed hu beinenu uveneichem uvein doreinu acharenu la'avod et avodat YHWH lefanav</strong>: &lsquo;it is a witness between us and you and between our generations after us, that we do perform the service of the LORD&rsquo; — the altar as <em>ed</em> (witness/testimony) is a category familiar from ancient Near Eastern treaty monuments: <em>masseboth</em> (standing stones) and boundary markers served as covenant witnesses (cf. Gen 31:44-52, Laban and Jacob&rsquo;s witness-heap). The altar&rsquo;s function is not sacrificial but testimonial — a physical declaration of covenant participation available for future generations to point to.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>veyomru eleynu ue'el doreinu machar veamarnu re'u et tavnit mizbeach YHWH</strong>: &lsquo;and in the future when they say to us or to our descendants: look, the copy of the altar of YHWH&rsquo; — the witness-altar is designed as an argument for intergenerational covenant inclusion. If future children ask &ldquo;what right do you have?&rdquo;, the altar is the answer: our fathers built this as a copy of the altar of YHWH; we have the same relationship to the God of Israel as the western tribes. The altar is a piece of tangible evidence that can be pointed to in a dispute about covenant standing.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>chalilah lanu mimreod laYHWH ulesubvav hayom me'acharei YHWH livnot mizbeach le'olah laminchah velazevach milevad mizbeach YHWH Eloheinu asher lifnei mishkano</strong>: &lsquo;far be it from us to rebel against the LORD and turn away from him today, to build an altar for burnt offerings, grain offerings, or sacrifices, other than the altar of the LORD our God that stands before his tabernacle!&rsquo; — the conclusion is the categorical denial combined with the affirmation: there is one altar, the one before the tabernacle; we have not built another. The <em>chalilah lanu</em> (far be it from us) is the strongest possible Hebrew expression of rejection and horror at the suggested possibility.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Phinehas and the leaders heard the Transjordan tribes&rsquo; explanation and were pleased. The narrative satisfaction of the delegation&rsquo;s acceptance is the resolution of the tension built since v12. The theological issue (potential covenant breach) is resolved by the Transjordan tribes&rsquo; explanation; the community is not divided. Phinehas — who stopped the Peor apostasy with violent action — here is the instrument of reconciliation through hearing and discernment. Both actions serve covenant fidelity; the choice between them depends on what the situation actually requires.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>hayom yadanu ki betochenu YHWH asher lo me'altem baYHWH hama'al hazeh az hitzaltem et bnei Yisrael miyad YHWH</strong>: &lsquo;today we know that the LORD is among us, because you have not committed this breach of faith against the LORD — now you have rescued the people of Israel from the hand of the LORD&rsquo; — Phinehas&rsquo;s declaration reads the Transjordan tribes&rsquo; faithfulness as evidence of divine presence among the whole people. Their non-sin is not merely a private relief but a communal rescue: the whole assembly was in danger of divine wrath for a <em>ma'al</em> that turned out not to have occurred. Faithfulness in a potential crisis situation rescues more than the faithful — it protects the whole community.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Phinehas and the leaders return from Gilead to Canaan and bring back a good report to the Israelites. The narrative structure is complete: crisis (v10-12), investigation (v13-29), resolution (v30-31), report (v32-33). The structure mirrors diplomatic and legal processes that are recognizable across cultures: confrontation, inquiry, adjudication, reconciliation. The covenant community resolves its internal crisis through process, not through preemptive violence.</p>",
    "33": "<p><strong>vayitav hadavar be'einei bnei Yisrael vayevarachu Elohim bnei Yisrael</strong>: &lsquo;the report pleased the Israelites, and they praised God&rsquo; — the community&rsquo;s response to the resolution is worship, not merely relief. The conflict that threatened civil war is resolved by the Transjordan tribes&rsquo; fidelity, and the proper response is praise to YHWH. The connection between covenant resolution and worship is consistent: &ldquo;Therefore, if you are offering your gift at the altar and there remember that your brother has something against you… first go and be reconciled to your brother, then come and offer your gift&rdquo; (Matt 5:23-24).</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>vayiqre'u livnei Reuven uvnei Gad et hamizbeach ki ed hu veinenu</strong>: &lsquo;the Reubenites and Gadites named the altar Ed — &ldquo;Witness&rdquo; — saying, &ldquo;It is a witness between us that the LORD is God&rsquo;&rdquo; — the naming closes the narrative with the altar&rsquo;s function permanently inscribed in its name. The altar named <em>Ed</em> (witness) stands as a permanent testimony to covenant unity across the Jordan — not a rival worship site but a monument to the shared covenant that transcends the river boundary. Every future generation that sees the altar knows: the Transjordan tribes are part of the covenant people of YHWH.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p><strong>vayehi miyamim rabim achar asher heniyach YHWH leYisrael mikol oyveihem misaviv</strong>: &lsquo;a long time afterward, when the LORD had given rest to Israel from all their surrounding enemies&rsquo; — Joshua&rsquo;s farewell speech is set in old age, after the rest has been established. The <em>menuha</em> (rest) is both military and covenantal: the land is secured, the Levitical cities distributed, the covenant renewed at Ebal. Joshua speaks from the vantage point of accomplished mission. Hebrews 4:8 cites this rest as insufficient: &ldquo;for if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken of another day later on.&rdquo; The rest of the completed conquest points beyond itself.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Joshua summons all Israel — their elders, heads, judges, and officers — the full leadership structure of the covenant community. The formality of the summons matches the gravity of what follows: a farewell speech of a leader who has completed his work, knows he is dying, and needs to leave the community with the essential word. The succession of Moses and Joshua both end with farewell addresses (Deut 31-34; Josh 23-24): the pattern of the dying leader&rsquo;s final testimony is foundational to the covenant tradition.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>atem re'item et kol asher asah YHWH Eloheichem lekhol hagoyim ha'eleh mifinechem ki YHWH Eloheichem hu hanilochem lachem</strong>: &lsquo;you yourselves have seen all that the LORD your God has done to all these nations — for it is the LORD your God who has fought for you&rsquo; — the appeal to direct experience (<em>atem re'item</em>, you yourselves have seen) grounds the farewell in testimony rather than argument. Joshua does not deduce or reason to divine faithfulness; he points to what the community witnessed. This is the consistent biblical mode of covenant instruction: redemptive history is not a doctrine to be accepted but a testimony to be received from witnesses.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>re'u hipeladeti lachem et hagoyim hanorotim ha'eleh lenachalah leshivtechem</strong>: &lsquo;I have allotted to you as an inheritance for your tribes these remaining nations&rsquo; — Joshua distinguishes the nations already defeated from those that remain. The promised land has been allotted even though not all of it is yet secured; Israel holds the land by right of divine allocation, not by the completion of military conquest. This is the &ldquo;already and not yet&rdquo; structure: the inheritance is theirs by divine gift, fully realized through ongoing obedience.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>vaYHWH Eloheichem hu yehdofem mifinechem veyorish otam mifinechem vishatem et artzam ka'asher diber lahem YHWH Eloheichem</strong>: &lsquo;the LORD your God will himself drive them out from before you and dispossess them — you shall possess their land, as the LORD your God promised you&rsquo; — the future completion of what is already begun rests on divine initiative (<em>hu yehdofem</em>, he himself will drive them). Israel&rsquo;s task is faithfulness; the driving-out is YHWH&rsquo;s action. The distinction between human covenant fidelity and divine accomplishment is maintained even in the military language.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>vachazaqtem me'od lishmor vela'asot et kol hakatuv besefer torat Moshe lebilti sur mimenu yamin usmol</strong>: &lsquo;be very strong to keep and to do all that is written in the Book of the Law of Moses, turning aside from it neither to the right nor to the left&rsquo; — Joshua echoes his own commission (1:7: &ldquo;do not turn from it to the right or to the left&rdquo;). The charge he received at YHWH&rsquo;s call he now passes to all Israel at his death. The <em>sefer torat Moshe</em> (Book of the Law of Moses) is the written Torah as the permanent deposit of covenantal obligation. Obedience to written Torah — not to oral tradition or to national interest — is the standard.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>lebilti lavo bago'im ha'eleh hanorotim ha'eleh ushvem lo tizkiru</strong>: &lsquo;so that you may not mix with these nations remaining among you, nor make mention of the names of their gods&rsquo; — the separation principle: not merely avoiding worship of other gods, but not even invoking their names. The prohibition on naming (<em>lo tizkiru</em>) reflects the covenantal significance of naming: to invoke a name is to acknowledge a power, to enter a relationship of dependence. The same principle appears in Paul&rsquo;s instruction: &ldquo;whatever is true, whatever is honorable…  think about these things&rdquo; (Phil 4:8) — cognitive separateness from false allegiances precedes behavioral separateness.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>ki im beYHWH Eloheichem tidbaqun ka'asher asitem ad hayom hazeh</strong>: &lsquo;but you shall cling to the LORD your God, as you have done to this day&rsquo; — <em>dabaq</em> (cling) is the verb of intimate attachment: Gen 2:24 (&ldquo;a man shall cling to his wife&rdquo;), Ruth 1:14 (&ldquo;Ruth clung to her&rdquo;). The covenant relationship with YHWH requires the same total, exclusive, intimate attachment as marriage. The phrase &ldquo;as you have done to this day&rdquo; is both commendation and standard: continue what has characterized you so far. The farewell speech assumes continuity with the achieved faithfulness of the conquest generation.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>vayorish YHWH mifinechem goyim gedolim ve'atsumim</strong>: &lsquo;the LORD drove out before you great and strong nations&rsquo; — the completed-tense summary of what YHWH did is the basis for what YHWH will continue to do. The God who drove out great nations for Israel is not less capable now; the appeal to divine track record is an appeal to divine character, which does not change. The rhetorical function is identical to Paul&rsquo;s argument in Rom 8:32: &ldquo;He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all, how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?&rdquo;</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>ish echad miachem yirdof elef ki YHWH Eloheichem hu hanilochem lachem ka'asher diber lachem</strong>: &lsquo;one man of you puts a thousand to flight, because the LORD your God fights for you, as he promised you&rsquo; — the arithmetic of divine empowerment: one warrior plus YHWH equals a thousand opponents. The mathematics is not military but covenantal — it measures not force-ratios but the asymmetry between human weakness and divine strength. Lev 26:8 promises the same disproportionate effectiveness: &ldquo;five of you shall chase a hundred, and a hundred of you shall chase ten thousand.&rdquo;</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>venishmartem me'od le'nafshoteichem le'ahavah et YHWH Eloheichem</strong>: &lsquo;be very careful to love the LORD your God&rsquo; — the charge to love (<em>ahavah</em>) frames covenant obedience as affection, not merely legal compliance. The Shema&rsquo;s command to love YHWH with all heart, soul, and strength (Deut 6:5) is the ground of all specific obligations; Joshua&rsquo;s farewell charge returns to this foundation. The specific dangers (vv12-13) follow from this positive command: they are threats to the love-relationship, not merely to legal standing.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>vechi shuv tashuvu udevaqtem beyeter hagoyim ha'eleh hanorotim ha'eleh itchem uhitchatantem bahem uveim bahem veyim bachem</strong>: &lsquo;for if you turn back and cling to the remnant of these nations remaining among you and make marriages with them&rsquo; — the prohibited mixing is precisely at the point where covenant love is expressed most intimately: marriage. The Deuteronomic prohibition of intermarriage (Deut 7:3-4) is grounded not in ethnic purity but in covenant fidelity: intermarriage with those who worship other gods will turn your heart away (Deut 7:4). <em>Dabaq</em> (cling) appears here negatively — clinging to the nations rather than to YHWH is the betrayal of the marital metaphor of v8.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>yada tede'u ki lo yoshif YHWH Eloheichem lehoresh et hagoyim ha'eleh mifinechem vehay lahem lepach ulemokesh uleshot betzidchem ulecicotzim be'einechem</strong>: &lsquo;know for certain that the LORD your God will no longer drive out these nations before you — they shall be a snare and a trap for you, a whip on your sides and thorns in your eyes until you perish from this good land&rsquo; — the covenantal warning is vivid and cumulative: <em>pach</em> (snare), <em>mokesh</em> (trap), <em>shot</em> (whip), <em>tzikotzim</em> (thorns). The fourfold image of entanglement, blinding, and pain captures the progressive degradation of a community that allows idolatrous influence into its life. The language is repeated in Judg 2:3, where the fulfillment of the warning is announced.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>vehinei anochi holech hayom bederech kol ha'aretz veyeda'atem bechol levavchem uvechol nafshechem ki lo nafal davar echad mikol hadvarim hatovim asher diber YHWH Eloheichem aleichem hakol ba lachem</strong>: &lsquo;behold, I am going today the way of all the earth, and you know in your hearts and souls, all of you, that not one word has failed of all the good things that the LORD your God promised concerning you — all have come to pass&rsquo; — Joshua&rsquo;s death-announcement (&ldquo;I am going today the way of all the earth&rdquo;) precedes the final testimony. The dying man&rsquo;s witness to divine faithfulness is the most credible: a person about to stand before YHWH has no reason to exaggerate divine goodness. <em>Lo nafal davar</em> (not one word fell) — repeating 21:45 at the farewell speech&rsquo;s climax — is the book&rsquo;s central claim and theological heart.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>vehayah ka'asher ba aleichem kol hadavar hatov asher diber YHWH Eloheichem aleichem ken yavi YHWH aleichem et kol hadavar hara</em> ad hashmiido otchem me'al ha'adamah hatovah hazot asher natan lachem</strong>: &lsquo;just as all the good things that the LORD your God promised concerning you have come to pass, so the LORD will bring upon you all the evil things until he has destroyed you from off this good land&rsquo; — the covenant is symmetric: the same divine faithfulness that fulfilled the blessings will fulfill the curses. This is not punitive cruelty but the consistent application of covenant logic: YHWH&rsquo;s word is reliable in both directions. Hebrews 10:28-29 applies the same logic to the new covenant: if Torah-violation brought certain judgment, how much more will rejection of the Son.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>baavrechem et brit YHWH Eloheichem asher tzivah etchem vahalacitem va'avaditem elohim acherim vehishtachavitem lahem vacharah af YHWH bachem ve'avadtem meherah me'al ha'aretz hatovah asher natan lachem</strong>: &lsquo;if you transgress the covenant of the LORD your God, which he commanded you, and go and serve other gods and bow down to them — then the anger of the LORD will be kindled against you, and you shall perish quickly from off the good land that he has given you&rsquo; — the final verse of the farewell speech is the conditional that governs everything: covenant transgression → idolatry → divine anger → loss of the land. The entire history of Israel from Joshua to the exile is the story of this conditional being fulfilled. The &ldquo;good land&rdquo; (<em>ha'aretz hatovah</em>) frames both the gift (v15, <em>asher natan lachem</em>) and the potential loss: what is given as covenant gift is forfeited by covenant breach. The farewell ends where it began — with the covenant as the absolute center of Israel&rsquo;s existence.</p>"
  }
}

